def good_subarrays(nums, k):
    count = 0
    for i in range(len(nums)):
        frequency = {}
        for j in range(i, len(nums)):
            frequency[nums[j]] = frequency.get(nums[j], 0) + 1
            if len(frequency) > k:
                break
            if len(frequency) == k:
                count += 1
    return count
```

    The algorithm iterates through each element of the array and starts another loop from that element to the end. In the inner loop, we maintain a frequency map/dict/object which stores the frequency of the integer occurrence in the subarray starting from `i` to the current element of the inner loop. We update the frequency of the integer at each step of the inner loop.

If the size of the frequency map/dict/object is greater than `k`, we break the inner loop as it's not a good subarray. If the size of the frequency map/dict/object is exactly equal to `k`, we increment the count of good subarrays.

Lastly, we return the count of good subarrays after iterating through the entire array.

